{"title": "Hustling the Mark", "content": "A common con game in fiction, particularly in comedy. It works like this: Someone challenges a person to a \"friendly game\" of something, be it cards, some kind of sport or something else. At first, they seem to be bad at the game and will repeatedly lose to the other person. Then they will suggest a wager. The minute the wager is made, they suddenly become good at the game and beat the other person hands down. A longer, and more expensive version, is to lose a series of small bets and then apparently attempt to bluff the mark into going away with a very large, dangerous bet that completely overwrites the previous losses.\n\nThe defeated party has just been the unfortunate victim of a clever scam artist. In other words, the mark has just been hustled. Big time.\n\nOften involves the use of Obfuscating Stupidity. A subtrope of Short Con. Truth in Television. There have been many famous hustlers in Real Life. In fiction, the apparent mark will often turn out to be a better hustler than the con-artist.\n\nNote: This trope does not refer to ANY kind of scam. It specficially refers to a particular con involving a competition of some sort.", "url": "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/HustlingTheMark", "media_links": ["/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Manga/HikaruNoGo", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Manga/TheLegendOfKoizumi", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Anime/YuGiOh", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Webcomic/DorkTower", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Franchise/ArchieComics", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/ComicBook/LuckyLuke", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Disney/BigHero6", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/TheHustler", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/TheColorOfMoney", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/Diggstown", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/EnterTheDragon", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/TheSting", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/TheGrand", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/HowIUnleashedWorldWarII", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/Maverick", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Creator/AbbottAndCostello", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/OceansEleven", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Cr